      'Moneylending (usury) was considered sinful by the Christian Church but was essential to commerce. Christians were forbidden from charging interest, so Jewish moneylenders filled an economic necessity while being despised for doing so — a contradiction the play explores.',
      'The trial scene reflects Elizabethan ideas about the superiority of Christian mercy over Old Testament law. However, Shakespeare complicates this hierarchy by showing the Christians acting without mercy, inviting a more critical reading than the surface theology suggests.',
      'The play was written shortly after the execution of Roderigo Lopez, a Portuguese Jewish physician accused of trying to poison Queen Elizabeth I. This event may have heightened anti-Jewish sentiment and influenced the play\'s reception.',
      'Elizabethan theatre was exclusively male, so female characters like Portia and Jessica were played by boy actors. The cross-dressing scenes therefore involved boys playing women playing men, adding layers of complexity to the play\'s exploration of identity and disguise.',
